In article <gradyCszKHq.9vH@netcom.com>, Grady Ward <grady@netcom.com> wrote:
>Do you also then agree that it was legally and ethically wrong for Phil
>to appropriate the name "RSA" withut legal license?

Huh?  Phil said that PGP uses RSA, which in fact it does.  That's
description, not appropriation.  If PGP used a knapsack algorithm
and he were to describe it as RSA, then there would be a problem.
Even if a name is trademarked, you don't have to get permission to
use it; you just can't abuse it.

